SyncMaster 913V 'SAM0115' ddccontrol test report
by htamas, 5-6 February 2006

legal stuff
--------
This test report was created using a ddccontrol version having
experimental support for my monitor and was probably subject to
mistakes in my interception of the results. I hereby disclaim all
liabilities arising from my disclosure of this information.
This report can be freely copied, of course. I expressedly
permit the authors of ddccontrol to use this information to
further improve their software.
Product names mentioned are trademarks of their respective owners.

test environment
--------
this report applies to:
* Samsung SyncMaster 913V 19" LCD monitor (vga input only)
  (model 913V N, model code GS19ESSS/EDC, type no GH19LS)
  available via pci:01:00.0-2
* MSI FX5600XT-TD128 nVidia GeForce FX 5600 video card
* SuSE Linux 10.0 OSS using kernel 2.6.13-15.7-smp (i686)
* ddccontrol CVS version '3.1', as of 2006-02-05
* ddccontrol-db CVS version, as of 2006-02-05
  (particularly SAM0115.xml and SAM01B4.xml)

methodology
--------
the following types of tests have been carried out:
* forward test
    changed a control using ddccontrol and checked
    for changed osd settings and other visible effects
* reverse test
    changed individual osd settings and ran a diff on the
    ddccontrol -d output before and after
* combined test
    changed a control using ddccontrol and checked which
    other controls did it affect
I ran a forward test on each control returned by 'ddccontrol -p -c -d',
a reverse test on each setting visible in the osd menu and a combined
test on all non-obvious controls. The tests have been carried out by
passing -r and -w arguments to ddccontrol, using dedicated
shell scripts as well as manually invoking ddccontrol.
Note that I don't know anything special about the monitor's internals
so I'm considering it as a black box during this test.

results
--------
I got lots of "Invalid response, first byte is 0x51, should be 0x6e"
error messages, which makes me think that responses beginning with
0x51 should be accepted as well. However, I don't know what is the
difference between the two response types. Such error messages seem
not to occur when using the quite primitive controls (such as
brighness, contrast, hpos, vpos, coarse and fine) and are specific
to the control written. For some controls, I get only one of this,
for others, I get 2 or 3 (i.e. there are controls which give me
sometimes 2 and sometimes 3, but none that gives e.g. sometimes 1
and sometimes 2). Rarely, it also occurs when
"Reading EDID and initializing DDC/CI at bus pci:01:00.0-2..."
but mainly on writing controls. One of my guesses is that a response
starting with 0x51 has something to do with persistence (keeping
settings when monitor is turned off).

Some examples:
(the numbers vary but the sequence always starts with 51)
